The Economy of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly topics in the news, and therefore many would likely say it is a war.
But this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would like to end every war and act of violence just as we would like to put an end to poverty, hunger, and climate change and ensure access to education for all people.
However, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We need to set priorities, and for that, an economic cost-benefit analysis can be utilized.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals, in their view, would be the smartest.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the deployment of resources that would otherwise, for example, be used in fighting hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence in society—murder and especially violence against women and children—poses a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every death among the casualties of a civil war, nine people die as a result of interpersonal violence, and for each two combatants who perish, one child is killed.
In 2008, globally, 418,000 people were killed, and far too many countries recorded murder rates of more than 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization considers an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person's life and society $9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against national revenues worldwide, this form of violence alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GSP).   Note: "Bruttosozialprodukt" is not a standard economic term in English. The equivalent term is "gross domestic product" (GDP). So a more accurate translation might be:  "Measured against national revenues worldwide, this form of violence alone costs 1.7% of the global gross domestic product (GDP)."
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be in a condition that can be quantified at 1.7% of GDP.
Let's compare this with the much lower costs of civil wars, which account for about 0.2% of global GDP.
However, that is still much less than the largest source of violence there is: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members in the past year.
This includes women who were beaten, forcibly married at a young age, exposed to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honour," and circumcised.
According to a cautious estimate, the subsequent costs for society alone due to violence by partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents in 80% of cases.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but around 15% of children experience what the UN refers to as severe physical punishment every month.
This includes hits to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are struck repeatedly and as severely as possible with an object.
This suffering affects about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid funds is currently flowing into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs that are borne by society and individuals cry out for some action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there are still very few reliable insights into where the limited resources should be best allocated.
What can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be targeted more effectively.
Large sums of aid money are allocated for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with a "crime prevention" component.
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but it is obvious that many things could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained professionals can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life for children, enhance their physical and mental health, and lower the costs of welfare and procedural expenses.
One dollar spent on this program generates a benefit of 14 US dollars: thus, it is an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program named SASA! is working in Uganda.
(Swahili for "Now!") This helped reduce the number of cases by half by spreading the view that violence in partnerships is unacceptable.
This is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures were taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach—包括对酒精销售的时间限制、重新夺回公共空间以及警察和司法系统改革的措施——谋杀率在2004年降至每10万人中21人。
This is still a high number, but it is far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of considerable importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on the better enforcement of existing regulations showed that physical assaults could be reduced in a highly cost-efficient manner, with the benefit-to-cost ratio being 17 to 1.
We know that we still do not have enough information, but two points are clear: Firstly, domestic violence against women and children entails costs amounting to 8 trillion US dollars per year for society and thus represents a huge – and much too neglected – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can address some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, reducing domestic violence belongs to the narrower selection of goals for the next development targets of the world.
